2026-03-20T12:09:40.7124474-04:00 | attempt-11 | area=evaluation | hypothesis=The benchmark still mixes unsupported capability columns and brittle output/file-shape checks, producing noise and at least one false negative on valid two-prompt YAML. Remove unsupported `agent`/`extension` profiles, replace `file-contains` with output-only structural checks, and relax prompt-shape assertions to validate semantics instead of exact block layout. | classification=false-negative | result=KEPT | before=0/6 pass with 2 unsupported columns and hard file-read failures in prior state | after=0/6 pass with 0 unsupported cells, clean structural checks, and prompt-specific checks that now pass when the generated YAML is semantically correct | reason=The measured pass rate did not rise because current outputs are still genuinely off-contract on shared compare requirements (`no-skill`/`skill`, runtime-relative workspace path, danger-full-access + network enabled). Keep the benchmark changes because they remove benchmark noise and make remaining failures attributable to real output defects.
2026-03-20T12:24:29.3341731-04:00 | attempt-12 | area=evaluation | hypothesis=The benchmark should still verify that the agent actually writes `deliverables/compare.yaml`, but `file-contains` causes noisy hard failures. Add a safe JavaScript assertion that requires the file to exist, contain the remote skill path, and match the returned YAML. | classification=coverage-gap | result=KEPT | before=0/6 pass with output-only shared checks | after=0/6 pass with file-write coverage restored and no regression in interpretability | reason=This closes a real measurement gap in the skill contract: the task asks to create the file, not only print YAML. The latest sampled failures still look like true negatives because both the file-write assertion and the shared structural assertion fail together on off-contract outputs.
